      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>In 1937 a group known as the Players of the International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union wrote, produced and starred in <emph render="italic">Pins and Needles</emph>, a "witty and tuneful" musical revue satirizing organized labor in general and the ILGWU in particular.  Numbers include "Sing us a song with social significance," Doin' the reactionary," and "One big union for two."  The play was so successful that it was given a regular run at the Labor Stage in New York, with new skits and songs added periodically to keep the production fresh and topical.  More than one performance was standing room only.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Pins and Needles Collection</emph> contains printed material (programs and published music scores) from various productions of the musical revue, and manuscripts (an original score for the song "Mene, Mene, Tekel" by Harold Rome).</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>Printed material is arranged chronologically where possible but many items are undated.</p>
      </arrangement>
      
      <relatedmaterial encodinganalog="544 1">
         <head>Related Material</head>
         <p>Belfer Audio Archive has numerous sound recordings of Pins and Needles performances.  Please refer to &summitref; to locate these items.</p>
      </relatedmaterial>
      
